# SPEC: flowmetrics warehouse app (v0)

> **Status.** Draft v0 — load-bearing decisions marked with **[D-N]**.
> Open questions tracked in §13. Iterate against this; don't build from
> it yet.

> **Defaults committed for the v0 draft** (each is revisitable; called
> out so review focuses on what to flip, not what's missing):
>
> - **[D-1]** Deployment tier: small team server (Tier 2). Single-user
>   laptop (Tier 1) is a subset, supported but not the primary mode.
> - **[D-2]** Auth: OIDC against the team's existing identity provider,
>   with a local-account fallback for solo / homelab installs.
> - **[D-3]** First user: generic — designed to be configurable rather
>   than tuned for one team. Ships with example contracts.
> - **[D-4]** Source auth: GitHub App + Jira OAuth 2.0 by default. PAT
>   supported only in single-user mode (Tier 1) and explicitly
>   discouraged in docs for any shared deployment.
> - **[D-5]** Agent API: read-only by default. Writes (refresh trigger,
>   contract edit) require a separate confirmation flow that LLMs
>   cannot transparently complete.

---

## 1. Goals & non-goals

### Goals

1. **Move flow-metrics computation off interactive runtime.** ETL ingests
   from GitHub/Jira on a schedule, materialises Parquet, and exits. The
   runtime serves charts, MCS forecasts, and agent queries by reading
   that Parquet — never by calling GitHub/Jira during a request.
2. **Make slicing dynamic.** Team, initiative, risk class, severity,
   epic, time window — all queryable from one fact table without
   re-fetching anything.
3. **Make MCS fast.** Sub-second forecast responses at standard sample
   sizes (10k simulations). The slow part of MCS — gathering the
   training distribution — moves into ETL.
4. **Make secrets hard to leak.** Token storage, request lifecycle,
   error handling, and logs all designed so that a stolen container
   image or a leaked log file cannot exfiltrate a GitHub/Jira token.
5. **Make agents first-class consumers.** OpenAPI-documented JSON API
   that LLM-driven tools can call, with read-only-by-default safety.

### Non-goals (v1)

- Multi-tenant SaaS. One installation = one organisation's data.
- Real-time / second-by-second metrics. The metric is a leading
  indicator measured at standup cadence; minute-granular doesn't add
  value.
- Replacing GitHub Insights / LinearB / Jellyfish at feature parity.
  The point is the Vacanti-grade contract + agent-readability, not a
  marketplace product.
- Custom dashboard builder. v1 ships a fixed set of report types; the
  agent API lets users build their own UI if they need one.
- Mobile-native UI. The web app is desktop-first; responsive but not
  optimised for phones.

---

## 2. Architecture

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                       Browser / Agents                          │
│  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────  │
│  HTMX pages with Vega-Lite charts        |  LLM-driven tools     │
└────────────────────────────────┬────────────────┬───────────────┘
                                 │ HTTPS          │ HTTPS / OAuth
                                 ▼                ▼
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                       RUNTIME SERVICE                            │
│                       (FastAPI, uvicorn)                         │
│  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────  │
│  /                  HTMX pages                                  │
│  /api/v1            JSON API (OpenAPI 3.1)                      │
│  /admin             contract editor, refresh trigger            │
│  /auth              OIDC callback / local login                 │
│                                                                  │
│  Reads only. Never calls GitHub/Jira. Hot in memory:            │
│    • DuckDB connection (pooled)                                 │
│    • Throughput index (pre-computed per contract)               │
│    • Contract YAML (parsed, validated)                          │
└────────────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────┘
                                 │ reads Parquet
                                 ▼
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                    DATA LAYER (Parquet store)                   │
│  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────  │
│  /data/                                                          │
│    work_items/    contract_id=X/year=Y/month=M/items.parquet    │
│    transitions/   contract_id=X/year=Y/month=M/items.parquet    │
│    throughput/    contract_id=X/scope=S/throughput.parquet      │
│    contracts/     {hash}.yaml + {hash}.metadata.json            │
│    runs/          contract_id=X/run_id=…/manifest.json          │
└────────────────────────────────▲────────────────────────────────┘
                                 │ writes Parquet (atomic rename)
                                 │
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                       ETL SERVICE                                │
│                       (APScheduler in-process,                  │
│                        OR external cron + CLI)                  │
│  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────  │
│  For each contract on its schedule:                              │
│    1. Fetch scope from GitHub/Jira (cached, paginated)          │
│    2. Replay event stream against contract stages               │
│    3. Build work_items + transitions rows                       │
│    4. Compute throughput index for forecast scopes              │
│    5. Atomic write to Parquet (write .tmp + rename)             │
│    6. Append run manifest                                       │
│                                                                  │
│  Holds secrets in memory only for fetch duration.               │
└────────────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────┘
                                 │ HTTPS
                                 ▼
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  GitHub API (GraphQL + REST)      |    Jira API (REST)          │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

### Why the ETL / Runtime split is load-bearing

- **Different performance envelopes.** ETL is IO-bound, rate-limited,
  minutes-to-hours per refresh. Runtime is CPU-bound, must respond in
  ≤1s. Coupling them means runtime inherits ETL latency; splitting
  them means runtime never touches the network.
- **Different failure modes.** Rate-limit throttling, API outages, and
  authentication failures all live in ETL. Runtime continues serving
  the last successful snapshot regardless.
- **Different scaling.** N teams = N ETL schedules (parallel,
  independent). One runtime serves them all.
- **Different security postures.** ETL holds secrets; runtime doesn't.
  An attacker who compromises the runtime cannot exfiltrate tokens
  because they're not there.
- **Replayability.** Re-deriving the fact table from cached raw API
  responses is local and fast. Re-fetching from GitHub is slow and
  rate-limit-bounded. The split makes the difference auditable.

### Deployment topologies

The split allows three deployment shapes from the same codebase:

1. **Bundled** — single Docker container, ETL runs in-process via
   APScheduler. Simplest. Default. Works for everything up to ~20
   contracts on daily refresh.
2. **Split processes** — same image, two deployments: `flow-runtime`
   and `flow-etl`. ETL has secret-store access; runtime doesn't.
3. **Kubernetes-native** — runtime as a Deployment, ETL as a CronJob.
   Same image, different commands. Independent scaling, independent
   restart, secrets injected only into the CronJob.

