## 4. Data model

### 4.1 `work_items` (fact table)

One row per piece of work. Columns derived from event replay + contract
metadata mapping. Hive-partitioned by `contract_id` and year/month for
prune-on-read.

| Group | Column | Type | Source |
|---|---|---|---|
| Identity | `source` | enum | github / jira |
| | `repo` | string | for URL only — not a primary slice |
| | `item_id` | string | PR# / issue# / jira-key |
| | `item_type` | string | pr / issue / epic / story / … |
| | `title` | string | |
| | `url` | string | |
| | `author` | string | login or accountId |
| | `is_bot` | bool | derived from contract exclusions |
| Lifecycle | `created_at` | timestamp | |
| | `completed_at` | timestamp | null if in-flight |
| | `closed_at` | timestamp | may differ from `completed_at` |
| | `cycle_time_days` | double | derived |
| | `age_days` | double | now − created_at for in-flight |
| Stage durations | `time_in_<stage>_h` | double | one column per contract stage |
| | `total_active_h` | double | Σ wip-stage durations |
| | `total_wait_h` | double | Σ non-wip-stage durations |
| | `flow_efficiency` | double | active / (active + wait) |
| Phase durations | `pickup_time_h` | double | PR open → first non-author review |
| | `review_time_h` | double | first review → merge |
| | `post_approval_wait_h` | double | last approval → merge |
| Slicing metadata | `team` | string | from contract metadata mapping |
| | `initiative` | string | |
| | `risk_class` | string | |
| | `severity` | string | |
| | `area` | string | |
| | `release` | string | |
| | `epic_key` | string | parent epic / closing issue |
| | `linked_keys` | list[string] | cross-source links |
| Activity | `commit_count` | int | |
| | `review_count` | int | |
| | `comment_count` | int | |
| | `changes_requested_count` | int | |
| | `last_activity_at` | timestamp | |
| Provenance | `contract_id` | string | hash of contract YAML |
| | `materialised_at` | timestamp | when ETL produced this row |
| | `run_id` | string | ETL run that produced this row |

### 4.2 `stage_transitions` (long table)

Source of truth for per-stage durations. The fact table's `time_in_*`
columns are derived from this; the contract can change without
re-fetching from GitHub/Jira.

| Column | Type |
|---|---|
| `source` | enum |
| `item_id` | string |
| `entered_at` | timestamp |
| `exited_at` | timestamp (null if still in stage) |
| `stage` | string |
| `is_wip` | bool |
| `signal` | string (which event drove the transition) |
| `contract_id` | string |

### 4.3 Throughput — computed on demand, cached in memory

Earlier drafts pre-computed a `throughput_index` Parquet table per
named scope. That was wrong: **the runtime must support dynamic
windowing and slicing** (e.g. "past 14d for team-a + team-b"), so
pre-computing every (scope × window) combination is combinatorial.

Instead, throughput for MCS is computed **on demand** from the fact
table:

```sql
-- pseudocode; the runtime constructs this from filter+window params
SELECT date_trunc('day', completed_at) AS d, COUNT(*) AS completions
FROM work_items
WHERE contract_id = $contract
  AND completed_at BETWEEN $training_start AND $training_end
  AND team IN ('platform', 'data')
  AND NOT is_bot
GROUP BY d
ORDER BY d
```

DuckDB scans a 100k-item fact table for one contract + window + filter
in ~5–20ms. The MCS step (`np.random.choice` from the resulting array)
adds another ~10ms. Total runtime forecast cost: well within the
80ms p50 budget without any pre-computation.

**Caching.** Throughput arrays are keyed by `(contract_id, filter_hash,
training_window)` and held in a process-local LRU. Cache key includes
the contract's `run_id` so the cache invalidates automatically when
ETL writes a new run for that contract.

**When pre-computation might be needed.** If/when a single contract's
fact table grows past ~1M items, or a deployment supports many
concurrent forecast users with diverse slices that defeat the LRU,
revisit pre-computing per-day completions denormalised by the most
common slice dimensions. Tracked under §13 open questions.

### 4.4 Contracts (config artifacts)

YAML files stored in `data/contracts/`, hashed for identity. Loaded
into memory at startup; reloaded on file mtime change without restart.

See §5.

### 4.4.1 Contracts vs Views — the two axes of "configuration"

Two completely different lifecycles. Worth naming so they don't get
conflated:

| Aspect | **Contract** | **View** |
|---|---|---|
| Lifetime | Durable; weeks to months | Ephemeral; one query / one UI interaction |
| Defines | Stages, metadata extraction, exclusions, scope of what ETL fetches | Time window + slice filters for *this* read |
| Who edits | Admins / team leads | Anyone running a query, every interaction |
| How edited | YAML in `data/contracts/` (or admin UI form) | URL params, UI controls, API filter args |
| Triggers | ETL re-run (next scheduled or manual refresh) | Nothing — pure read from existing Parquet |
| Versioning | Hashed; old data preserved under old hash | Not versioned (it's a query, not state) |
| Examples | "We added a Design stage" / "Drop dependabot" | "Show me last 14 days, teams a+b" |

**The runtime guarantee.** Any report, any forecast, any aggregation
accepts a (window, filter) pair and operates on that slice without
touching the contract. The contract defines *what was fetched and
how it's parsed*; the view defines *what the user wants to see right
now*.

This separation is what makes the UI feel responsive: users can
change windows and toggle team filters all day without invoking ETL
or rewriting YAML. Contract editing — the slow path — is a separate,
admin-gated UX.

### 4.4.2 View shape

A view is just a parameter bag, never persisted as state (in v1).
The canonical shape, used by API params and UI controls:

```python
@dataclass(frozen=True)
class View:
    contract_id: str
    # Time window
    since: date | None              # default: contract's history_window_days
    until: date | None              # default: today
    training_window_days: int = 30  # for forecasts; user-tunable in UI
    # Slice filters — any column on work_items is filterable
    filters: dict[str, list[str]]   # e.g. {"team": ["a", "b"], "severity": ["1"]}
    excludes: dict[str, list[str]]  # negative filters
    # Behaviour
    include_in_flight: bool = True
    include_bots: bool = False      # bots excluded by default
```

All filters compose conjunctively (`AND`); within one filter key the
values are disjunctive (`team IN (a, b)`).

### 4.4.3 Saved views (deferred to v2)

Common views might warrant naming: "weekly platform retro,"
"quarterly initiative roll-up." v2 can persist `SavedView` records in
DuckDB with a slug, owner, and the parameter bag. v1 ships URL-
parameterised views only — share-by-link is good enough.

### 4.5 ETL run manifest

For each ETL run, a JSON manifest:

```json
{
  "run_id": "01HXKZ…",
  "contract_id": "sha256:…",
  "started_at": "...",
  "completed_at": "...",
  "scope_query_count": 12,
  "api_calls": {"github": 47, "jira": 0},
  "rate_limit_remaining": 4731,
  "items_fetched": 312,
  "items_updated": 47,
  "errors": [...]
}
```

Used for observability and for the admin UI's "last refresh" panel.

