## 5. Contract format

```yaml
contract:
  name: acme-platform-team
  version: 3
  description: |
    Platform team's PR-driven workflow. Inherits org-base for stage
    taxonomy; overrides metadata extraction for our labelling
    conventions.
  inherits: org-base

  scope:
    source: github
    query: "org:acme is:pr is:merged repo:acme/svc-a repo:acme/svc-b"
    # OR for Jira:
    # source: jira
    # project: PLATFORM
    # jql: 'project = PLATFORM AND statusCategory = Done'

  stages:
    - { name: Triage,        query: "label:triage",            wip: false }
    - { name: Design Doing,  query: "label:design/doing",      wip: true  }
    - { name: Design Done,   query: "label:design/done",       wip: false }
    - { name: Build Doing,   query: "label:build/doing",       wip: true  }
    - { name: Build Done,    query: "label:build/done",        wip: false }
    - { name: In Review,     query: "is:open review:none",     wip: false }
    - { name: Approved,      query: "is:open review:approved", wip: false }
    - { name: Merged,        query: "is:merged",               wip: false }

  metadata:
    team:
      strategy: label_pattern
      pattern: "team-(.+)"
      default: "unowned"
    initiative:
      strategy: label_pattern
      pattern: "initiative-(.+)"
    risk_class:
      strategy: label_values
      values: ["expedite", "fixed-date", "intangible", "standard"]
      default: "standard"
    severity:
      strategy: label_pattern
      pattern: "sev-(\\d+)"

  exclusions:
    - "user:dependabot[bot]"
    - "user:renovate[bot]"
    - "label:duplicate"
    - "created:<2024-01-01"

  refresh:
    schedule: "0 6 * * *"     # daily 06:00 UTC
    in_flight_max_age_days: 180
    history_window_days: 90

  forecast_scopes:
    - { name: team_overall,        filter: {} }
    - { name: by_initiative,       group_by: initiative }
    - { name: by_severity,         filter: { severity: ["1","2"] } }
```

### Supported predicate vocabulary

Stages and exclusions accept a constrained subset of GitHub search
syntax — the subset whose history we can replay locally from timeline
events:

| Predicate | Replayed via |
|---|---|
| `label:X` | LabeledEvent / UnlabeledEvent |
| `is:open` / `is:closed` | ClosedEvent / ReopenedEvent |
| `is:draft` | ReadyForReview / ConvertToDraft |
| `is:merged` | MergedEvent |
| `assignee:X` | AssignedEvent / UnassignedEvent |
| `review:approved` / `review:changes_requested` / `review:none` | PullRequestReview state |
| `user:X` | item.author (static) |
| `created:<date` / `>date` | item.created_at (static) |
| Conjunctions (`AND`, space) | local conjunction |
| Negations (`-label:X`) | local negation |

**Unsupported:** `comments:>N`, `reactions:>N`, full-text search, regex
on title. Use these in `scope_query` (current-state filter) but not in
stage predicates (need history).

### Inheritance & override resolution

When a contract has `inherits: org-base`:

- Org-base's stages provide the **stage taxonomy**.
- Child contract can **redefine the query** for an inherited stage,
  but not rename it (stable column names across teams).
- Child contract can **add stages** at the end; insertion order matters
  for stage assignment.
- Child contract can **add metadata extractors** but cannot remove ones
  defined in the parent (so cross-team queries on `team` work
  uniformly).
- Multiple matches at stage assignment: **rightmost stage in declared
  order wins**. Same rule as our current label workflow.

### Validation

The contract is validated at load time:

- All stage queries use only supported predicates.
- Stage names are unique.
- Metadata extractor strategies are recognised (`label_pattern`,
  `label_values`, `assignee`, `field`).
- Exclusions are valid scope-query predicates.
- `inherits` resolves to a real contract.

Invalid contracts are rejected with line-level error messages. ETL
refuses to run; runtime continues serving the last good contract.

---

## 6. ETL service

### 6.1 Pipeline

For each contract on its schedule:

```
fetch_scope     → list of WorkItem source nodes (paginated from GH/Jira)
↓
replay_events   → list of (item, stage_transitions[]) per item, derived
                  locally from the fetched event timeline + contract
                  stage predicates
↓
build_facts     → flatten to one row per item with derived columns
↓
apply_metadata  → extract team/initiative/risk_class/… per contract.metadata
↓
apply_exclusions → mark or drop excluded rows
↓
compute_throughput → for each forecast_scope, daily completion counts
↓
materialise      → atomic write to Parquet (write .tmp, rename)
↓
manifest         → write run summary to runs/
```

### 6.2 Scheduling

`APScheduler` (in-process) with per-contract cron expression. Defaults:

- `refresh.schedule: "0 6 * * *"` — daily 06:00 UTC
- Staggered start times automatically applied (no two contracts start at
  the exact same minute, even if their cron strings would).
- Refresh can be triggered manually from `/admin` (requires admin role).

### 6.3 Refresh tiering

| Tier | Items | Refresh policy |
|---|---|---|
| **Frozen** | `completed_at < window_start` and `contract_id` unchanged | Read from existing Parquet, never re-fetched, never re-derived |
| **Closed-recent** | `completed_at` within last `history_window_days` | Re-derived from cache (events may have been backfilled) |
| **In-flight** | `completed_at is null` | Re-fetched and re-derived |

Cache key includes `(scope_query, window, source)`. Cached responses are
permanent for closed windows; in-flight items use a fresh fetch every
refresh.

### 6.4 Source authentication

| Source | Tier 1 (laptop) | Tier 2 (team server) |
|---|---|---|
| GitHub | PAT in OS keyring | **GitHub App + installation token**; private key in secret store |
| Jira | PAT in OS keyring | **OAuth 2.0**; refresh token in secret store |

Tokens are read into memory exactly once per ETL run; never logged,
never serialised to disk. ETL records the GitHub App installation
ID + last token rotation date in the run manifest for audit.

### 6.5 Rate-limit handling

GitHub: each query reports its cost; ETL backs off when remaining
budget < 200 points. Jira: REST is request-counted; ETL applies
exponential backoff on 429.

ETL never blocks the runtime when throttled — it logs, completes what
it can, and writes a partial run manifest. Next scheduled run picks up.

### 6.6 Failure modes

| Failure | Behaviour |
|---|---|
| One contract's scope query fails (invalid syntax) | Skip that contract; log; runtime continues serving last good snapshot |
| GitHub rate limit | Wait for reset OR complete partial run + retry next schedule |
| Jira auth expired | Retry once with refresh token; if refresh fails, mark contract degraded; admin UI surfaces it |
| Schema-drift in source (new event type) | Unknown event type → ignored with WARN log; doesn't fail the run |
| Parquet write fails partway | `.tmp` files cleaned up on next run start; never leaves a partial in place |

---

## 7. Runtime service

### 7.1 Performance budget

Non-functional requirements drive the implementation choices below.

| Operation | p50 budget | p99 budget |
|---|---|---|
| Dashboard page render (server-side, HTMX) | 100ms | 400ms |
| Single-slice chart query (DuckDB scan + aggregate) | 50ms | 200ms |
| MCS forecast at 10k sims, 30-day horizon | 80ms | 250ms |
| JSON API response | 80ms | 300ms |

All measured cold-cache assuming a 100k-item fact table. Hot-cache is
faster.

### 7.2 Query layer

- **DuckDB embedded** opened once per process; connection re-used.
- Hive-partitioned reads — DuckDB prunes irrelevant `contract_id` and
  `year=…/month=…` partitions automatically.
- Common aggregations pushed down to DuckDB (no row materialisation in
  Python for chart data).
- Polars used for any custom transforms that don't fit cleanly in SQL
  (zero-copy interop with DuckDB).
- No ORM. SQL strings are parametrised and live in a query module;
  static analysis catches injection at lint time.

### 7.3 MCS engine

The performance-critical operation. Three optimisations stack:

1. **Pre-computed throughput index** (built in ETL). Runtime never
   computes daily counts from the fact table during a forecast.
2. **Vectorised sampling** via numpy:
   ```python
   completions = throughput[contract_id, scope_hash]   # cached array
   sims = np.random.choice(completions, size=(n_sims, n_days)).sum(axis=1)
   percentiles = np.percentile(sims, [50, 70, 85, 95])
   ```
3. **Process-local cache** of throughput arrays keyed by
   `(contract_id, scope_hash, training_window)`. Cache invalidated when
   ETL writes a new run manifest for that contract (file watcher).

Result: forecast response time is dominated by JSON serialisation, not
computation. The runtime can serve 100+ concurrent forecast requests on
a laptop-class machine.

### 7.4 Web UI

- **HTMX + server-rendered Jinja templates.** No SPA build step, no
  state management library, no separate front-end repo.
- **Vega-Lite embedded via CDN script tags** — same as current
  flowmetrics report rendering.
- **Page inventory (v1):**
  - `/` — landing: list of contracts, last-refresh status, links to
    each
  - `/contracts/<id>` — per-contract dashboard with all report types
  - `/contracts/<id>/efficiency` — efficiency drill-down + per-item
    table
  - `/contracts/<id>/aging` — WIP aging with hover-detail
  - `/contracts/<id>/forecast` — MCS forecasts; date and count
  - `/contracts/<id>/scatterplot`
  - `/contracts/<id>/cfd`
  - `/contracts/<id>/items/<source>/<item_id>` — single-item lineage
    (the explainability view)
  - `/admin` — contract editor, refresh trigger, token rotation
  - `/admin/contracts/<id>/edit` — YAML editor with syntax+schema
    validation
- **Server-side rendering** keeps page load <400ms p99. Interactivity
  (zoom, filter, drill-down) is HTMX swaps, not client state.

### 7.5 The "explain why this item is in this stage" view

For the contract to be trustworthy, every fact-table row must explain
itself. Per-item page shows:

- Current stage + why (which event drove the most recent transition)
- Full transition history (one row per stage entry with timestamp and
  signal)
- All metadata extractions and which event/label produced each
- All exclusions evaluated (passed/failed each one)
- Direct link back to GitHub/Jira for ground truth

This is what makes the contract debuggable. Without it, the contract
is a fancier black box.

---

## 8. API surface

### 8.1 Design principles (Hyrum-aware)

These principles govern every endpoint in this spec. Cite them in PR
review when an endpoint design drifts.

1. **Contract first.** The schema is the spec. Implementation follows.
   FastAPI route handlers reference typed Pydantic models; OpenAPI
   3.1 is generated from those types, not hand-written.
2. **Hyrum's Law applies.** Any observable behaviour — field order,
   error message text, response timing, undocumented quirks —
   becomes a commitment once agents and dashboards depend on it.
   Design implications:
   - Be intentional about what you expose. If a field is in the
     response, it's a contract.
   - Don't leak implementation details (DuckDB error stacks, file
     paths, internal IDs that aren't stable across runs).
   - Plan deprecation at design time. See §8.7.
   - Tests aren't a defense — agents will depend on things the tests
     don't check.
3. **One-Version Rule.** No `/api/v2` alongside `/api/v1`. Extend
   `v1` additively. A new major version exists only when a breaking
   change is forced and a 6-month deprecation window has elapsed.
4. **Validate at boundaries only.** Pydantic parses every request
   body and every query-string params dict. Internal code trusts
   those typed objects; no defensive re-validation. Source-fetched
   data (GitHub/Jira) is validated where it lands in the canonical
   model.
5. **Prefer addition over modification.** New fields are optional.
   Existing field types don't change. Existing fields don't get
   removed without deprecation.
6. **Predictable naming** (locked):
   - URL paths: plural nouns, no verbs (`/work-items`, not `/getItems`).
   - Path segments: kebab-case (`work-items`, `forecast-when-done`).
   - Query params: snake_case (`since`, `training_window_days`).
   - JSON field names: snake_case (`cycle_time_days`, `created_at`).
   - Boolean fields: `is_*` / `has_*` / `can_*` prefix.
   - Timestamps: RFC 3339 in UTC, field suffix `_at`.
   - Durations: numeric with unit-suffixed name (`pickup_time_h`,
     `cycle_time_days`).
   - Enum values: snake_case (`in_progress`, `changes_requested`),
     matching the values used in the data layer.

### 8.1.1 What IS a commitment, and what is NOT

Naming the two categories explicitly because the Hyrum's-Law trap is
real. The credibility rule (§6 in `SPEC.md`) says tests assert the
human-readable strings; the API design rule says don't let those
strings become an agent contract.

**Commitments (frozen; change = breaking):**

- URL paths, HTTP methods, status codes, error `type` URIs.
- Field names, field types, enum values, units.
- The set of fields in any successful response.
- The set and meaning of standard view params.
- Pagination model (cursor opacity, ordering guarantees).
- Authentication mechanism, header names, token formats.

**NOT commitments (free to change without versioning):**

- The exact prose of `headline`, `key_insight`, `next_actions[]`,
  and `caveats[]` strings. These are for human display.
- The order of items in `next_actions[]` and `caveats[]` arrays
  (treat as set semantics).
- Field order in JSON objects (semantically irrelevant; JSON spec).
- Whitespace inside HTML responses.
- Internal IDs that aren't documented (run IDs are documented;
  internal DuckDB row IDs are not).
- Server-rendered HTML page structure (HTMX-driven, may change).
- Performance numbers (the budget in §7.1 is a target, not a
  contract).

### 8.1.2 The headline / structured-fields separation

A direct consequence of 8.1.1. Reports today emit prose like
`"85% confident at least 12 items finish in the next 14 days (by
May 31, 2026)"`. Tests assert the prose. But agents that scrape the
prose to drive automation freeze the wording.

The API response carries both:

```json
{
  "headline": "85% confident at least 12 items finish in the next 14 days (by May 31, 2026).",
  "headline_template": "{confidence}% confident at least {count} items finish in the next {days} {day_word} (by {target_date}).",
  "headline_values": {
    "confidence": 85,
    "count": 12,
    "days": 14,
    "day_word": "days",
    "target_date": "2026-05-31"
  }
}
```

**Rule for clients:**
- **Human UIs** render `headline` directly. May change between
  releases for clarity; not a contract.
- **Agents and automation** read `headline_values` and (optionally)
  re-render via `headline_template`. The values are typed and stable;
  the template strings are stable per major version.

Same pattern applies to `key_insight`, every entry in `next_actions[]`,
and every entry in `caveats[]`. All carry a parallel structured form.

### 8.2 Shape & envelope

OpenAPI 3.1, generated by FastAPI from typed Pydantic models. All
endpoints under `/api/v1`. Versioning policy in §8.8; deprecation in
§8.9.

Every successful response carries a standard envelope:

```json
{
  "data": <endpoint-specific payload>,
  "meta": {
    "contract_id": "sha256:abc123…",
    "contract_version": 3,
    "run_id": "01HXKZ…",
    "materialised_at": "2026-05-18T06:01:23Z",
    "view": {
      "since": "2026-04-18",
      "until": "2026-05-18",
      "filters": {"team": ["platform", "data"]},
      "excludes": {},
      "training_window_days": 30
    },
    "request_id": "01HY3M…"
  }
}
```

- `meta` is structurally identical across every endpoint. Agents can
  detect staleness via `materialised_at`; correlate logs via
  `request_id`; reproduce a query via `view`.
- List-shaped responses additionally carry `pagination` (see §8.5).
- `data` is the only field whose shape varies per endpoint.

### 8.3 Endpoints (v1)

Every read endpoint accepts the **standard view params** — they define
the slice and window for that query. None of them imply or trigger a
contract change.

**Standard view params (apply to every read endpoint):**

| Param | Type | Default | Meaning |
|---|---|---|---|
| `since` | date | `today - contract.history_window_days` | window start |
| `until` | date | today | window end |
| `training_window_days` | int | 30 | for forecasts |
| `filter[<col>]` | repeatable string | none | e.g. `?filter[team]=a&filter[team]=b` |
| `exclude[<col>]` | repeatable string | none | negative filter |
| `include_in_flight` | bool | true | include items with `completed_at is null` |
| `include_bots` | bool | false | include `is_bot=true` rows |

```
# Reads — view params apply to all
GET   /api/v1/contracts                           list contracts
GET   /api/v1/contracts/{id}                      contract details + last run
GET   /api/v1/contracts/{id}/work-items           filtered list (+ standard view params)
        ?limit=…&cursor=…
GET   /api/v1/contracts/{id}/work-items/{src}/{itemid}
        full item detail + stage lineage
GET   /api/v1/contracts/{id}/aggregate
        ?metric=cycle_time|flow_efficiency|throughput
        &group_by=team|initiative|severity
        &percentile=50,70,85,95
        + standard view params
GET   /api/v1/contracts/{id}/forecast/when-done
        ?items=N&start=DATE
        + standard view params (filter[team]=…, etc.)
        + training_window_days
GET   /api/v1/contracts/{id}/forecast/how-many
        ?days=N&start=DATE
        + standard view params
        + training_window_days
GET   /api/v1/contracts/{id}/cfd
        + standard view params

# Discovery (helps UIs build slice controls)
GET   /api/v1/contracts/{id}/dimensions
        → {team: [...], initiative: [...], severity: [...], ...}
        Distinct values for each metadata column, for populating filter widgets.

# Admin (write) — requires admin role; never triggered by view changes
POST  /api/v1/contracts/{id}/refresh              trigger ETL run
PUT   /api/v1/contracts/{id}                      update contract YAML
POST  /api/v1/contracts/{id}:validate             dry-run validation
DELETE /api/v1/contracts/{id}
```

The `/dimensions` endpoint exists so the UI can build dropdowns and
filter widgets without hard-coding column values. It's a cheap
`SELECT DISTINCT` per metadata column, cached per `(contract_id, run_id)`.

### 8.4 Errors

Single error envelope, RFC 7807 (Problem Details for HTTP APIs):

```json
{
  "type": "https://flowmetrics.example/errors/validation",
  "title": "Validation failed",
  "status": 422,
  "detail": "Field 'since' must be a date earlier than 'until'.",
  "instance": "/api/v1/contracts/abc/work-items?since=2026-06-01&until=2026-05-01",
  "code": "VIEW_WINDOW_INVERTED",
  "field_errors": {
    "since": ["must be earlier than 'until'"]
  },
  "request_id": "01HY3M…"
}
```

**Required fields**: `type`, `title`, `status`, `code`, `request_id`.
**Optional fields**: `detail`, `instance`, `field_errors`, plus any
per-error-type extensions documented in OpenAPI.

The `code` is the machine-readable identifier and IS a commitment
(§8.1.1): agents may switch on it. The `title` and `detail` are
human-readable and may evolve.

**Status code policy:**

| Status | Use |
|---|---|
| 400 | Malformed request (un-parseable JSON, missing required field) |
| 401 | Not authenticated |
| 403 | Authenticated but not authorised for this resource |
| 404 | Resource not found OR (deliberately) hidden from this caller |
| 409 | Conflict (concurrent contract edit; version mismatch) |
| 422 | Validated as syntactically OK but semantically wrong (`since > until`, unknown enum value, unsupported predicate in stage query) |
| 429 | Rate-limited |
| 500 | Internal error — body MUST NOT include stack traces, file paths, or DuckDB error text. Generic `code: INTERNAL_ERROR` + `request_id` only. |
| 503 | Service degraded (no successful contract run available; ETL is processing a refresh) |

**Token redaction.** A logging+response middleware scrubs anything
matching `gh[ps]_[a-zA-Z0-9_]+`, JWT triplets, or
`Authorization:.*` substrings from `detail` and any nested error
context. Tested in `tests/test_error_redaction_component.py`.

### 8.5 Pagination

Cursor-based, opaque to clients:

```
GET /api/v1/contracts/{id}/work-items?limit=50&cursor=eyJsYXN0X2lkIjoidWlkLW9wYXF1ZSJ9
```

Response envelope adds `pagination` to `meta`:

```json
{
  "data": [...],
  "meta": {
    "contract_id": "...",
    "pagination": {
      "next_cursor": "eyJsYXN0X2lkIjoiMTIzNCJ9",
      "has_more": true,
      "limit": 50,
      "total_estimate": 1247
    },
    "...": "..."
  }
}
```

**Commitments:**
- `next_cursor` is opaque (base64 of internal state); clients
  MUST NOT parse or construct it.
- Cursor stability: a cursor returned by run N is valid for
  subsequent reads against run N. After a new ETL run produces a
  newer `run_id` for the contract, cursors from the older run remain
  valid but may skip newly-added items or include items that have
  changed.
- `limit` default 50, max 500. Larger limits are rejected with 422.
- `total_estimate` is approximate (DuckDB count over the filtered
  set, sampled if expensive). NOT a contract — agents needing exact
  totals must paginate to exhaustion.
- Ordering is stable within a single pagination traversal (by
  `(completed_at DESC, item_id ASC)` for work-items; documented per
  endpoint).

### 8.6 Conventions for agents

- All list endpoints support `limit` + opaque `cursor`-style pagination.
- All time fields are RFC 3339 timestamps in UTC.
- Numeric metrics include units in the field name (`cycle_time_days`,
  `pickup_time_h`).
- Every response embeds the `meta` envelope (§8.2) so agents can
  detect stale data and reproduce queries.
- Errors follow §8.4. Token-bearing fields are scrubbed by middleware.
- Headlines and prose strings: see §8.1.2 — agents parse
  `*_values` and `*_template`, never the free-form prose.

### 8.7 Agent safety

- **Read endpoints** are GET-only, idempotent, safe for any LLM tool to
  invoke speculatively.
- **Write endpoints** are POST/PUT/DELETE, require admin role, and
  return a `confirmation_token` rather than executing immediately.
  Final mutation requires a second call with the token within 60s.
  This pattern is deliberately not transparently completable by a
  naïve agent loop; it requires explicit human approval.
- **Rate limits** per API key (separate from GitHub limits): 100
  req/min default, 10 req/min on forecast endpoints (since they're
  CPU-heavier).

### 8.8 Versioning policy (One-Version Rule)

We maintain exactly one major API version at a time. `/api/v1` until
an incompatible change is forced; then `/api/v2` with a 6-month
co-existence window during which both are served and `/api/v1` returns
a `Sunset` header (RFC 8594) + `Deprecation` header (RFC 9745).

**Non-breaking changes** (allowed in-version, no version bump):
- Adding new optional fields to request/response.
- Adding new endpoints.
- Adding new enum values to fields whose Pydantic model uses
  `extra='ignore'` semantics (clients must already tolerate unknown
  values).
- Adding new query params with sensible defaults.
- Tightening validation errors (returning more specific `code` for
  cases that previously returned a generic one).

**Breaking changes** (require new major version):
- Removing or renaming any committed field (§8.1.1).
- Changing the type or units of an existing field.
- Removing an endpoint or path segment.
- Changing the meaning of an enum value.
- Changing pagination semantics.
- Changing the structure of the `meta` envelope.
- Changing the URL of an existing endpoint.

### 8.9 Deprecation procedure

When deprecation is unavoidable:

1. **Announce** in a release note + the `Deprecation` header on the
   affected endpoint, with `Sunset: <date>` ≥ 6 months out.
2. **Add the replacement** alongside the deprecated form, NOT in
   place of it.
3. **Mirror behaviour** for the deprecation window — both endpoints
   work, returning structurally compatible data where possible.
4. **Trace usage.** Log requests to the deprecated endpoint with
   `api_key_id` + `request_id`. Admin dashboard surfaces a "still in
   use by" list before sunset.
5. **Remove only after** the sunset date AND the trace shows zero
   usage in the last 30 days. If usage persists, extend the sunset.

Deprecation is a write event, recorded in the `audit.duckdb` log.

---

## 9. Security & threat model

### 9.1 Threat actors

| Actor | Capability | Concerns |
|---|---|---|
| External attacker (network) | Hit the public web endpoint | Auth bypass, SSRF via contract edits, token exfil through error messages |
| Authenticated user (unprivileged) | Use the web UI as a normal team member | Privilege escalation, data exfil beyond their team scope |
| Malicious agent | Has an API key (acquired legitimately or stolen) | Trigger expensive operations, exfil via aggregations |
| Compromised container | Has filesystem + memory access on the host | Token theft from memory, secret-store keys, Parquet exfil |
| Disgruntled admin | Has full system access | Out of scope for v1 — assume admin honesty |

### 9.2 Token storage (per deployment tier)

| Tier | GitHub | Jira | Local users |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Tier 1** (laptop) | OS keyring | OS keyring | n/a — single user |
| **Tier 2** (team server) | GitHub App private key in env var (mounted from secret manager) | OAuth refresh token in env var (mounted from secret manager) | bcrypt hashes in DuckDB `users` table |

Tokens are read into memory **only** during an ETL run. They never
appear in:
- Log files (logger middleware redacts anything matching `gh[ps]_*` or
  JWT-shaped strings)
- Parquet files (no source attribute is ever extracted into a column
  that could hold secret material — explicit allow-list of attributes)
- API responses (error sanitiser replaces token-shaped substrings with
  `[REDACTED]`)
- Process titles or argv (CLI accepts secrets via env or stdin only)

### 9.3 Network egress

- ETL allow-list: `api.github.com`, the configured Jira host, OIDC
  IdP. Any other outbound HTTP is blocked at the application layer.
- Contract YAML cannot specify arbitrary URLs (no webhooks, no
  user-supplied fetch targets in v1). SSRF surface area is therefore
  near-zero.

### 9.4 Authentication & authorisation

**Authentication:**
- **Tier 1**: no auth (single user on `127.0.0.1`).
- **Tier 2 default**: OIDC against a configured IdP. Sessions are
  short-lived (8h), refresh via OIDC silent re-auth.
- **Tier 2 fallback**: local user accounts in `data/users.duckdb`,
  argon2 password hashing, optional TOTP.

**Authorisation:**
- Three roles: **viewer**, **editor**, **admin**.
- **viewer**: read-only access to all `/api/v1/*` GET endpoints and all
  `/contracts/*` web pages.
- **editor**: can edit contract YAML they own (matched by `owner_team`
  field in contract metadata).
- **admin**: full access including token rotation and contract
  deletion.

**API keys:**
- Personal API keys (32-byte random, stored hashed) for agent access.
- Keys are scoped: a key can be read-only or read-write, and can be
  scoped to specific contracts.
- Keys are displayed exactly once on creation; never retrievable.

### 9.5 CSRF / XSS / injection

- CSRF tokens on every state-changing form post.
- `Content-Security-Policy` headers blocking inline scripts except the
  Vega-Lite CDN bundle.
- All user-supplied content rendered through Jinja's autoescape.
- SQL queries are parametrised; query module enforces this.
- Contract YAML is parsed with `yaml.safe_load` (no custom tags).

### 9.6 Logging

- Structured logs (JSON, one line per event) to stdout.
- Redaction middleware applied to **all** log output before write.
- No bodies of API responses logged; only metadata (path, status,
  latency, user_id, contract_id).
- Audit log for admin actions (contract edit, token rotation, user
  creation) stored separately in `data/audit.duckdb`.

### 9.7 Backups

The Parquet store is the backup unit. `data/` rsync'd nightly to a
cold-storage location. The contracts directory is also version-
controlled in a git repo (separate from the application source).

Secrets are **not** backed up by the application. Secret-manager
backup is the deployer's responsibility (whatever they're already
doing for their other systems).

---

## 10. Deployment topology

### 10.1 Bundled (default Tier 2 install)

One container:

```
flowmetrics:latest
  ENTRYPOINT: uvicorn flowmetrics.app:app
  CMD: --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8000
  ENV:
    FLOW_DATA_DIR=/data
    FLOW_CONTRACTS_DIR=/data/contracts
    FLOW_OIDC_ISSUER=https://idp.example.com
    FLOW_OIDC_CLIENT_ID=…
    FLOW_OIDC_CLIENT_SECRET=…   (from secret manager)
    FLOW_GITHUB_APP_ID=…
    FLOW_GITHUB_APP_PRIVATE_KEY=…   (from secret manager)
    FLOW_JIRA_CLIENT_ID=…
    FLOW_JIRA_CLIENT_SECRET=…   (from secret manager)
  VOLUMES:
    /data
```

Reverse proxy (Caddy / nginx) terminates TLS, forwards to `:8000`.

### 10.2 Split (Kubernetes-native)

```
Deployment: flow-runtime          (replicas: 1)
  CMD: uvicorn flowmetrics.app:app
  ENV: (no source secrets — read-only)
  Volumes: read-only mount of /data

CronJob: flow-etl                 (schedule: "0 * * * *")
  CMD: flow etl run --all-contracts
  ENV: (source secrets injected here only)
  Volumes: read-write mount of /data
```

ETL secrets are never present in the runtime pod's environment.

### 10.3 Local dev (Tier 1)

```
uv run flow serve
# Runs both ETL (APScheduler) and runtime in one process
# Tokens from OS keyring
# Binds 127.0.0.1:8000 only
# No auth (single user)
```

---

## 11. Operations

### 11.1 Observability

- `/healthz` — process liveness (no auth).
- `/readyz` — readiness: returns 503 if no contract has a successful
  run within `2 × refresh.schedule` interval.
- `/metrics` — Prometheus-format runtime metrics: request count by
  endpoint, response time histograms, ETL last-run age per contract,
  DuckDB query times, MCS request rate.
- ETL run manifest accessible at `/admin/runs/<contract_id>` for
  per-run inspection.

### 11.2 Schema evolution

- Adding a column to `work_items` → Parquet handles natively (old rows
  read as NULL).
- Adding a stage to a contract → next ETL run produces new column on
  rows for that contract; rows from other contracts remain NULL.
- Renaming a stage → ETL rebuilds from `stage_transitions` (cheap).
  Downstream tooling expecting the old column name breaks — surfaced
  in CI via the runtime's typed query module.
- Removing a stage → row's `time_in_<stage>_h` column remains as a
  historical artefact; new ETL runs write NULL.

### 11.3 Re-derivation

When a contract changes:

1. Old contract's Parquet rows are not rewritten (immutable history).
2. New `contract_id` (= new hash) gets its own partition.
3. UI shows both contract versions; current-data queries use the
   active one. Historical comparison queries can union across.

Re-deriving the full warehouse from raw cache + new contract takes
seconds (no network IO).

### 11.4 Runbook scenarios

- **"Forecast is stale"** — check ETL run manifest for that contract;
  re-trigger from `/admin` if needed.
- **"GitHub API failures"** — inspect last run manifest's error list;
  often a rate-limit; resolves on next schedule.
- **"Contract change crashed runtime"** — runtime continues serving
  last good contract; admin UI shows the validation error inline.
- **"Token rotation"** — admin UI button rotates GitHub App / Jira
  OAuth credentials; old credentials revoked at the provider.

---

## 12. Out of scope (v1)

Explicit list — these are real asks that we deliberately defer.

- **Multi-tenancy.** One install = one org's data. Tenant isolation,
  per-tenant secret stores, row-level security all deferred.
- **Real-time / webhook-driven updates.** Refresh is cron-only.
  Webhook listeners considered for v2.
- **Custom dashboard builder.** v1 ships fixed report types. Users who
  need custom views use the JSON API.
- **Mobile-first UI.** Responsive but not optimised for phones.
- **Alerting / notifications.** No "FE dropped below 10%" emails.
  Consumers integrate the API.
- **PR-level recommendations.** No "this PR should be split"
  suggestions. We surface data, not prescription.
- **Source adapters beyond GitHub / Jira.** GitLab, ADO, Linear all
  deferred to v2+.
- **Historical migration from another tool.** We start fresh from the
  configured scope window.

---

## 13. Open questions

These need answers (or explicit deferral) before implementation
starts:

1. **OIDC IdP shape for Tier 2.** Do we ship configurations for the
   common ones (Okta, Google Workspace, Azure AD, Authentik), or just
   a generic OIDC client and let the deployer figure it out?
2. **Local user fallback in Tier 2.** Is "OIDC OR local accounts"
   needed, or "OIDC only" for shared deploys with local-only for
   solo? The first is more code; the second is cleaner.
3. **Contract editor UX.** YAML textarea with schema validation
   (simplest, lowest-value-add) vs structured form builder (higher
   work, much more accessible). Probably YAML for v0, form builder
   tracked separately.
4. **First-class agent use cases.** What specific agent prompts are
   we designing for? "Show me last week's flow efficiency for the
   platform team" — straightforward. "What should we work on next" —
   prescriptive, out of scope. We need a target prompt list to
   validate the API shape against.
5. **Storage scale ceiling.** Is local-disk Parquet enough, or do we
   plan for S3-compatible object storage from day 1? DuckDB reads
   both transparently; choice affects backup story only.
6. **Bootstrapping the org-base contract.** On first install, do we
   ship a sensible default contract, or require the admin to create
   one from scratch? Default is friendlier; depends on whether we
   want a guided onboarding flow.
7. **MCS scope cardinality.** A contract with 5 forecast scopes × 4
   common slices = 20 throughput indexes pre-computed per refresh.
   Manageable. A contract with high-cardinality `group_by initiative`
   (50 initiatives) blows up to 50+ indexes. Cap or compute-on-demand?
8. **Schema for the items page lineage view.** What exactly does the
   "why is this item in this stage" explanation look like as data?
   Per-item explainability JSON might want its own table.

---

## 14. Migration from current flowmetrics CLI

The current CLI commands (`flow efficiency`, `flow aging`, etc.) keep
working in v1, repointed at the warehouse:

- Each command reads from `data/work_items` + `data/transitions`
  rather than fetching from GitHub.
- If no warehouse data is found, the CLI falls back to direct fetch
  (current behaviour) and prints a warning recommending `flow init`.
- `flow init` is a new command that creates a default contract for a
  given repo and runs an initial ETL pass.
- `flow serve` starts the web app.

Existing scripts (`scripts/generate_samples.py`) become contract
producers: each `Repo` entry maps to a generated contract YAML.

---

## 15. v1 milestone & sequencing — vertical slices

**Principle.** Every slice ends with *a working page a human can open
in a browser and use to make a decision*. No "build the perfect data
layer in isolation, then put a UI on it" sequencing. Each slice
exercises the full stack — source → ETL → Parquet → DuckDB → API →
HTML — at narrow scope, and widens from there.

Acceptance for each slice is **"a human can do X in a browser within
N seconds and the answer is honest."** Not test coverage, not
architectural purity.

---

### Slice 1 — One chart from real data, end to end

**Goal.** A user runs `uv run flow serve`, opens `localhost:8000`,
and sees a cycle-time scatterplot for one hardcoded GitHub repo. No
controls yet, no auth, no contract editor.

**Touched layers:**
- Source adapter: existing GitHub fetcher
- ETL: minimum viable — fetch completed PRs in a fixed window, write
  one `work_items.parquet`
- Storage: Parquet on local disk (no partitioning yet)
- Runtime: FastAPI process, one route, DuckDB scan, Jinja template
  with Vega-Lite embed
- Contract: hardcoded in code; no YAML yet

**Acceptance.** Open the URL, see real PR data on a scatterplot with
P50/P85 reference lines. Page renders in under 1 second.

**Deliberately excluded.** Aging, CFD, forecast, filters, multiple
repos, contract YAML, auth, deployment.

---

### Slice 2 — Window controls + a second report

**Goal.** Same page now has a "since / until" date picker. Cycle-time
scatterplot updates when the user changes the window. Add aging chart
on the same page.

**Touched layers:**
- Runtime: HTMX swaps on form change; second DuckDB query
- ETL: also write `stage_transitions.parquet` (needed for aging /
  in-flight detection)
- Contract: still hardcoded

**Acceptance.** User drags the date window and both charts re-render
inside 500ms. Aging chart shows in-flight items with reference
percentile lines.

---

### Slice 3 — Metadata extraction + team filter

**Goal.** Page has a "filter by team" multi-select widget. Selecting
teams updates all charts. Item rows expose `team` column derived from
PR labels.

**Touched layers:**
- Contract: introduce YAML format with `metadata.team` extraction
  (label pattern). Contract is still file-based, edited by hand for
  this slice.
- ETL: re-run pipeline reads contract, populates `team` column
- Runtime: `/dimensions` endpoint feeds the widget; filter param wired
  through DuckDB query

**Acceptance.** User checks "platform" and "data" in the filter
widget, charts redraw showing only items from those teams.

---

### Slice 4 — Forecast (MCS) with same controls

**Goal.** New "Forecast" page using identical window + filter
controls. Renders the when-done and how-many distributions for the
selected slice.

**Touched layers:**
- Runtime: MCS endpoint, on-demand throughput from fact table, numpy
  sampling, Vega-Lite histogram
- Performance: validate the 80ms p50 budget against a real fact
  table; cache throughput arrays per (filter, window) tuple

**Acceptance.** "Given the last 30 days for team=platform, when will
the next 25 items finish?" — chart and percentile table render in
under 1 second.

---

### Slice 5 — Second source (Jira) on the same page

**Goal.** Same UI, but pointed at a Jira project. Validate that the
contract abstraction holds across sources. Optionally: a contract
that mixes Jira issues with GitHub PRs via stitching.

**Touched layers:**
- Source adapter: existing Jira adapter wired into the new ETL
- ETL: contract scope can be Jira; new contract YAML for it
- Runtime: source-agnostic — already works because all queries hit
  the same fact-table schema

**Acceptance.** Point the runtime at a Cassandra-flavoured contract;
same UI shows Jira-driven flow metrics. Cross-source filter ("show me
items where `linked_keys` is non-empty") works.

---

### Slice 6 — Contract editing UI + refresh trigger

**Goal.** Admin can edit the contract YAML in the browser, validate
it, and trigger an ETL refresh. No more SSH'ing to edit files.

**Touched layers:**
- Runtime: admin page, YAML textarea with client-side schema hints
  (server-side validation is authoritative)
- ETL: validation endpoint runs the parser; refresh endpoint queues
  an APScheduler job
- Auth: introduce *minimal* auth — single admin password via env var.
  Real OIDC arrives in slice 7.

**Acceptance.** Admin tweaks the contract (e.g. adds a new exclusion),
clicks "validate" (gets line-level errors if any), clicks "save,"
clicks "refresh now," watches the run manifest update, and sees the
charts reflect the change.

---

### Slice 7 — Multi-user auth + JSON API

**Goal.** Real team-shared deployment. OIDC login, role gating
(viewer/editor/admin), JSON API for agents. Same UI, same data —
properly access-controlled.

**Touched layers:**
- Auth: OIDC flow against a configured IdP; sessions; local-account
  fallback
- Authorisation: role middleware; per-contract `owner_team` semantics
- API: same DuckDB queries exposed as documented JSON endpoints; API
  key management page
- Logging: redaction middleware comes online here (sensitive material
  starts existing in this slice)

**Acceptance.** A team member logs in via SSO and sees the same
charts. An agent with a read-only API key can call `/api/v1/...`
endpoints and get JSON. An LLM tool cannot trigger a contract change
or refresh without explicit human approval.

---

### Slice 8 — Hardening + production deployment

**Goal.** Move the GitHub PAT off the laptop. GitHub App + Jira OAuth
2.0 wired in. CSP, CSRF, rate limits, audit log. Docker image with
the split-process topology supported. Threat-model walkthrough
documented.

**Touched layers:**
- Source auth: replace PATs with installation tokens / OAuth flow
- Security middleware: CSRF, CSP, redaction, rate limits all enabled
  by default (some were stub-only in earlier slices)
- Deployment: Dockerfile, docker-compose for local, Kubernetes
  manifests for split topology
- Ops: `/healthz`, `/readyz`, `/metrics`, audit log

**Acceptance.** The whole thing runs in Kubernetes with secrets
injected from a secret manager. Runtime pod has no source credentials
in its environment. Threat-model checklist in §9 is walked through
and signed off.

---

### Why this order

- **Slice 1 forces commitment to the architecture early.** If the
  ETL/runtime split is wrong, you find out before writing the
  contract parser, not after.
- **Each slice is independently shippable** in the sense that it
  produces a screenshot you could show someone.
- **Auth is deferred** until there's something worth protecting. Slice
  6 introduces a single admin password because that's the first slice
  where there's a state-changing UI; full OIDC arrives in slice 7
  when there are multi-user scenarios.
- **Hardening is the last slice on purpose** — not because security
  is unimportant, but because the threat surface is concrete only
  after the feature surface exists. Walking the threat model against
  a stub UI would produce a checklist that doesn't match the real
  system.

### What's deliberately NOT a slice

- "Refactor the canonical model" — happens inside slices as needed.
- "Write 100% test coverage" — not a deliverable.
- "Build the perfect contract editor" — Slice 6 ships YAML-textarea;
  better editor is v2.
- "Migrate samples to the new pipeline" — samples script keeps
  working; warehouse path is parallel until proven.

### Sequencing the work inside each slice

Within a slice, the order is always:

1. **Walk the slice as a user** — describe the click path and the
   resulting page out loud before writing any code.
2. **Stub the page first** — Jinja template with fake data so the
   shape is concrete.
3. **Wire the runtime endpoint** — return that fake data shape from a
   DuckDB query against an existing or synthetic Parquet.
4. **Wire the ETL** to produce the real Parquet.
5. **Replace fakes with real data top-to-bottom.**
6. **Refactor** — the TDD refactor step, applied to the slice as a
   whole.

This sequence keeps the human-facing artifact (the page) in front of
the technical work, not behind it.

---

**End of v0 draft.** Pull at any thread — defaults, scope, security
model, API shape, sequencing. The goal of this draft is to be specific
enough that disagreement is concrete.
